review_blob: Nice deep black with a thin tan head that fades quickly. Aroma is standard porter (coffee, light chocolate) with a faint but distinctive presence fresh hop earthiness. An excellent porter with mellow notes of coffee and heavily malty, the fresh hops present themselves towards the end with their distinctive bright and piney bitterness. A wonderful take on a porter and a unique way to showcase fresh hops, excellently done.

On tap at Epic Ales. Golden color with a very nice off-white head. Nicely floral hop aroma and flavor, not overwhelming and nicely balanced by the bittersweet malt. This is a pale that would kick the ass out of most offerings of may craft breweries, and its probably the weakest in the line. A true session ale with a complexity of character rarely seen in these times of extreme-beer-ridiculousness.

On tap at Epic Ales taproom. Deep brown with a generous head that recedes and laces nicely. Big malty presence nicely balanced by the earthiness of the mushrooms; this is smart, thinking-outside-the-box, actually adventurous brewing. Hops arent enough to lend the necessary counter to the big malt presence? Find something that does. Really exciting stuff coming from this place, making what I would consider to be the best beer in Washington.
Deep orange, small white head. Fresh citrus aroma, lovely bitterness at the front with a strong, sweet, malty finish. Full mouthfeel without being overbearing.

Hazy yellow with a nice persistent white head. Fresh aroma of chamomile, lemon and ginger. Tart, floral and refreshing taste with a pleasant bite and a clean finish. I cant believe this is made with rice. Lovely beer.

Pours a clear golden yellow, faint and quickly gone head. Smells and tastes like nothing. Not offensive, just boring. Could not taste the ginger at all. Really disappointed in this one, as I tend to love Left Hands stuff.

This one turned out far differently than I expected, but not in a bad way at all. Ours a deep brown with a fizzy tan head which dissipates pretty quickly. Not a lot of lacing. Aroma is tons of bitter coffee and a nice hint of cardamom. Flavor is a big hit of bitter coffee with the aforementioned cardamom finishing it off rather nicely. Not a hint of sweetness; I enjoy sweeter coffee beers but this is a very nice counterbalance to that. Really unlike anything Ive had, cant wait to see how this brewery moves forward as they grow.
Pours light amber with a medium white head. Big citrus aroma. Flavor is heavy citrus bitterness, good malt presence and a wonderful piney finish. One of the most well balanced IIPAs Ive had.
Deep, cloudy amber, small head. Little to no lacing or carbonation. Aroma and flavor of sweet malt, licorice and sweet, tart fruits.
beer_name: Flying Dog Horn Dog Barley Wine

review_blob: Dark brown/black pour, small tan head. Strong, sweet malt aroma. Flavor is light citrus, strong bitterness and big malt sweetness. Lots of character all over the map leads to a bold but well balanced beer.
Deep red with a small tan head that fades fast. Light on aroma but whats there is caramel, fruits and molasses. Strong malt presence with a lingering hop bitterness.

Pours dark gold with little to no head. Lightly piney aroma and flavor with a decent malt presence and a pleasantly bitter finish. A little disappointing, but definitely one to try again and re-rate if necessary.
Deep amber/brown with a medium but quickly receding tan head. Port and malty sweetness at the front with a mild oaky finish. Complex and interesting but very sessionable.
Deep red with small tan head that fades quickly but leaves nice lacing. Equal parts pine and citrus with a strong malt finish. Palate is pleasantly sweet and lingers a nice long while.

Medium amber, small white head with little lacing. Pleasant if faint aroma of earthy hops and lightly sweet malt. Excellent session beer, with a pleasant and well balanced flavor, but not especially exciting. Quite good for what it is.

Very piney scent with some earthy undertones. Flavor is the aforementioned pine with light citrus accents and a very prominent malt presence, most notably at the finish. Hoppy without being overpowering and perhaps the most well-balanced IIPA Ive yet to sample.

Light malt aroma, something else reminiscent of a porter (coffee?) but pretty mellow in that department. Pleasantly sweet taste with very little hop presence. Nothing at all spectacular but an enjoyable, sessionable dark beer.
Yellow, white head, little lacing. Heavy citrus, not a lot of balance. Lots and lots of carbonation. Pretty foul aftertaste. Maybe a bad bottle?

Citrusy hop aroma with some nice pine accents. Light amber with a medium sized, pillowy off-white head. Nicely bitter with the malt to balance it. Not sure if the name is especially fitting, but quite good.

Deep amber, light white head. Faint aroma of citrus hops. A little too hoppy without a solid enough malt presence for an ESB, not aggressive enough for an IPA. In a weird purgatory where its not quite big enough to carry itself but a bit too heavy for a session beer. Still good.
Fruity, sour nose. Deep brown, malty, slightly sweet, slightly sour. Good if not extraordinary.
Black with a small head that dissipates quickly. Not much aroma, but whats there is light hops. Hoppy. Tastes like a serviceable IPA with a slightly more prominent malt backbone.
Deep black, big tan head. Chocolate and coffee in the aroma with some sour undertones, semi-sweet chocolate, coffee and a lovely malt backbone. Quite good.
Lots of pine in the aroma and in the flavor. Light orange with a big pillowy head and nice lacing. Very crisp finish. Further proof that aggressively hopped beers should favor pine over citrus.

Light citrus hops with an earthy scent from the mate. Cloudy orange with a small head. Flavor is light hops, some malt and more of that mate earthiness. Not something I would want to drink all the time, but a really interesting experiment, the sort Id love to see more of.

Deep amber pour, thick off-white head, laces nicely. Big hop aroma with malty sweetness in the background. Quite impressively balanced; the hops are definitely at the forefront, but there is a molasses-y sweetness to the malt backbone that is surprising and lovely. Interesting that an East Coast brewery has created such a fitting tribute to Pacific NW hops. A wonderful beer.
Deep amber, thick tan head, nice lacing. Nutty, caramely, malty. Its a brown. Its pretty good.

Rather unappetizing watered-down cola pour, small white head, no lacing. Smoky and yeasty aroma, neither scent being especially pleasant. Predominate flavor is bitter hops, which does not work in a bock. Really thin, unpleasant mouthfeel.
Deep brown/black pour, thick off-white head. Aroma is coffee and malt. Strong coffee at the front, nice creamy finish. Another not-amazing-but-damned-solid Lagunitas offering.

Light orange with a medium tan head. Very strong and slightly artificial peach aroma. Flavor is less artificial peach and actually quite pleasantly fruity, although it gets a bit sweet fairly quickly. Fairly nice, but a bit too sweet for a session.

Deep brown with a medium off-white head. Some lacing. Yeasty, grainy nose. Thin mouthfeel and unpleasantly sour finish. Mild hop flavor with notes of yeast. Not terrible (and not as bad I am making it sound) but not especially good either.

Dark brown/black with a thinner-than-expected tan head and nice lacing. Roasted malts and a bit of coffee in the aroma, same in the flavor with some bitter chocolate and a nice floral hop finish. Very nicely balanced for such a big stout.
beer_name: Left Hand Fade To Black Vol. 1: Foreign Stout

review_blob: Pours a deep amber with no head. Flavor and aroma are malt and molasses. Tastes like something between an American strong and an oatmeal stout. Tastes less like it looks than perhaps any beer Ive ever had. Probably not something Id drink on its own too often, but goes quite well with Ethiopian food (imagine that.)

Very light notes of coffee and chicory in the aroma. Black with a medium sized, light brown head. Thin mouthfeel, light spiciness, underwhelming flavor. Seems like i should be a bit more interesting than it is on first impression.

Really nice aroma and color, let down by the head formation. The initial flavor is amazing; real cherries, not in any way artificial. Earthy and bitter. The second wave is very, very sweet, almost cloying. Definitely a small-quantity (by which I mean taster sized) sort of beer.
Light brown with a small, soapy, gray-ish head. Nutty malt with some mellow hops. Pretty unsatisfying mouthfeel and finish. Nice flavor up-front, kind of a let down at the end, still pretty solid.
Deep, thick black pour with dark tan head. Aroma of roasted malt, oak and coffee. Very bitter chocolate flavor with notes of wood and coffee.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Cloudy, deep amber with a very small, soapy, quickly dissipating head.  Somewhat faint aroma, mainly honey, mellow hops and nutty malt. Heavy palate, sweet and malty flavor.
beer_name: Hair of the Dog Doggie Claws (2003-)

review_blob: Pours a nice,rich orange with a pillowy off-white head. Lots and lots of juniper and nutmeg in the aroma. The first sip is like drinking a Christmas tree, and not necessarily in a good way. Mellows out a great deal from there, but still quite over-spiced, with an un-balanced coriander overtone. Might balance the spiciness with a higher alcohol content, but a bit too thin to qualify as a warmer. A decent session beer, but not really all that special.
beer_name: Anchor Our Special Ale (2005 and later)

review_blob: Deep brown pour, ten head, aroma of dark chocolate and a bit of coffee. Full mouthfeel, dry, bitter finish. Lovely.
Light golden pour, big pillowy white head. Corn, malt, zero hops. A cheap lager, but not bad for what it is, especially at a cost of $3.99/6 at 6.2%. Good party beer.
Opaque black with a thick tan head. Lots of citrus hops with notes of chocolate and faint malt sweetness. One of the better dark IPAs Ive had.
beer_name: Mad River Serious Madness Black Ale

review_blob: Pale amber, small head. Citrusy and very, very sweet. Interesting but a bit much.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: Draft. Deep black with a small, bubbly head. Aroma is of hops and...something else not as pleasant. I cant identify it but its a bit off. Almost astringent.
Deep ruby-amber, small white head. Citrusy and sweet, and interesting barleywine. Amazingly good value to boot.
Very light amber, off-white head. Very floral, very crisp, nice hop bitterness up front and a malty finish. Good stuff.
beer_name: Fish Tale Organic Winterfish Seasonal Ale

review_blob: Deep amber/ruby, light tan head. Oak, malt and alcohol in the aroma and taste. Heavy on the palate, with a bit of an acidic burn. Lovely.

Nice citrus hop aroma, deep orange with small-ish white head, nice lacing. Flavor and palate are a bit thin, promise is much greater than delivery. Seems like theres some definite room for improvement, which I mean in a positive way.
Aroma is chocolate, malt and some oatmeal; nice deep brown with small tan head. Very smooth oatmeal stout flavor with light coffee and chocolate notes.
